ECE592 Final Project

Forecasting Global Active Power using LSTM

Project by Rageeni Sah (UID - rsah)

Introduction

The energy consumbed by every house is recorded using electrical equipment (electrical meter boxes) and can be read directly any time. Hwever, the energy consumed by the electrical equipment is not available directly. The enery consumed by an electrical quipment is called 'Active Energy'. As per UCI source, an active energy consumption every minute in watt hour can be calculated using global_active_power, and house electrical meter readings (which is usually 3 reading due to three phases installation). If sub_metering_1, sub_metering_2 and sub_metering_3 are sub -meters reading then, an active energy comsumbed every minute (in hour watt) is given by:

global_active_power 1000 /60 - (sub_metering_1 + sub_metering_2 + sub_metering_3)*

where each of the measurements are in watt hour for every minute.

Problem statement¶

(global_active_power*1000/60 - sub_metering_1 - sub_metering_2 - sub_metering_3) represents the active energy consumed every minute (in watt hour) in the household by electrical equipment not measured in sub-meterings 1, 2 and 3. In other words,

active_energy = global_active_power*1000/60 - sub_metering_1 - sub_metering_2 - sub_metering_3

An active energy consumed can be forecasted by forecasting global_active_power, sub_metering_1, sub_metering_2 and sub_metering_3. In this project, the focus is limited on forecasting global_active_power at various period level (identified through analysis) considering the project timeline, dataset challenges and other uncertainities.

Dataset¶

The dataset used in the project is available as household_power_consumption.zip.

The dataset consist of 2075259 measurements gathered in a house located in Sceaux (7km of Paris, France) between December 2006 and November 2010 (47 months). Each row of the dataset represents information in a minute.

key data challenges:-

  • 25% of the rows have missing values. As the rows appear on random dates, handling the missing values would not be straight forward and demands analytical approaches.
  • In several months complete one day readings are missing. In such cases missing values imputation can not be done at minute level.
  • Missing values not represented in traditional ways.

Methodology¶

The process to build a global active power forecasting model is divided broadly into three major steps :-

  • Pattern identification among records with missing values. Missing values imputation decision is taken based on hidden pattern and identified in first step of the process. To identify a pattern, listed out dates having missing details and corresponding hours and minutes. The number of missing readings varies across dates. Missing details represented by '?' symbol are replaced with numpy null object before imputation. The missing values are inconsistent across date and minutes, thus same approach can not be used for imputation. Thus, a different approach has been followed based on information availability. Thus, the rules followed are:

    • If missing a minute information, replace with next minute information.

    • If missing data for two continous minutes, replace with subsequent next minute information.

    • For remaining cases, imputating with average of global_active_power. This approach is chosen to simply the process. However, a different approach can be picked like imputating values using previous hour same minute information. The former method is retained as of now as it does not seems to impact the overal data statistics before and after imputations.

  • Data preparation and data pattern identification at different time-frame levels. The original data is at minute time frame. To understand the pattern at higher time-frames levels, global active power is aggregated at hourly, weekly, monthly and yearly levels. The distribution are vailable in figs folder. Mostly time series data do have trend, seasonality and periodicity. In the current dataset, global active power distribution at daily, weekly, and monthly shows only periodicity and seasonality. Data sitribution at minute level do not have a strong pattern in it rather posses lot of noises.

  • Model training and evaluation

    • Training - Long Short Term Memory (LSTM) is a powerful deep learning architecture for learning from sequential or time series dataset. LSTM inbuilt capability to learn and memorise long and short term past information makes it one of the favorable predictive neural network model for forecasting time series information. Thus, LSTM is used for training on the dataset. The proposed architecture has single hidden layer with four nodes and adam optimiser is used for parameters optimization. Each of the model is trained for 2000 epoach and the data is normalised before passing to the training model.

    • Evaluation - Global active power forecasting involves training and validation of LSTM at hourly, weekly and monthly levels. The complete dataset (47 months of data) is split into training and validation sets in the ratio of 7:3. Model is trained on first 70% of the total data and remaining 30% data is used for validation. MAPE is used as model performance evaluation metric.

# helper functions
torch.manual_seed(1)
def data_preparation(training_set, sequence_window_size = 27):
    '''This function takes training dataset (in dataframe form) and returns PyTorch tensors.'''
    def data_slicer(data, seq_length):
        x = []
        y = []

        for i in range(len(data)-seq_length-1):
            _x = data[i:(i+seq_length)]
            _y = data[i+seq_length]
            x.append(_x)
            y.append(_y)

        return np.array(x),np.array(y)

    sc = MinMaxScaler()
    training_data = sc.fit_transform(training_set)

    seq_length = sequence_window_size
    x, y = data_slicer(training_data, seq_length)

    train_size = int(len(y) * 0.7)
    test_size = len(y) - train_size

    dataX = Variable(torch.Tensor(np.array(x)))
    dataY = Variable(torch.Tensor(np.array(y)))

    trainX = Variable(torch.Tensor(np.array(x[0:train_size])))
    trainY = Variable(torch.Tensor(np.array(y[0:train_size])))

    testX = Variable(torch.Tensor(np.array(x[train_size:len(x)])))
    testY = Variable(torch.Tensor(np.array(y[train_size:len(y)])))

    return dataX, dataY, trainX, trainY, testX, testY, train_size, sc


def plot_data(data_predict, dataY_plot, train_size, w_type = 'D', toPath = figPath):
    '''This function plots global active power at different time frames.
    w_type valid parameters {"D", "M","W"}.
    "D" stands for daily, "M" stands for monthly and "W" stands for weekly forecast. '''
    fileSuffix = ''
    title = 'Global Active Power Forecast'
    if w_type == 'D':
        xlabel = 'Daily'
        fileSuffix = 'daily'
    elif w_type == 'M':
        xlabel = 'Monthly'
        fileSuffix = 'monthly'
    elif  w_type == 'W':
        xlabel = 'Weekly'
        fileSuffix = 'weekly'

    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (30,6))
    plt.axvline(x=train_size, c='r', linestyle='--')
    yhat = dataY_plot[:train_size+1].tolist() + data_predict[train_size-1:].tolist()
    plt.plot(yhat, label = 'Forecast', color = 'orange')
    plt.plot(dataY_plot, label = 'Actual')
    plt.suptitle(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel('Global_active_power')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    fig.savefig(figPath + 'global_active_power_forecasted_'+fileSuffix+'.png', dpi = 300)

def mape(y, yhat):
    return sum(abs((y - yhat)/y))/len(y) * 100

def evaluate(model, dataX, dataY, sc, train_size):
    model.eval()
    train_predict = model(dataX)

    data_predict = train_predict.data.numpy()
    dataY_plot = dataY.data.numpy()

    data_predict = sc.inverse_transform(data_predict)
    dataY_plot = sc.inverse_transform(dataY_plot)

    mdf = pd.DataFrame({'y':data_predict.ravel()[train_size-1:], 'yhat':dataY_plot.ravel()[train_size-1:]})
    print('MAPE: {}%'.format(round(mape(mdf.y, mdf.yhat)), 4))

    return data_predict, dataY_plot

# LSTM model
class GAPforecast(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes, input_size, hidden_size, num_layers):
        super(GAPforecast, self).__init__()
        
        self.num_classes = num_classes
        self.num_layers = num_layers
        self.input_size = input_size
        self.hidden_size = hidden_size
        
        self.lstm = nn.LSTM(input_size=input_size, hidden_size=hidden_size,
                            num_layers=num_layers, batch_first=True)
        
        self.fc = nn.Linear(hidden_size, num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        h_0 = Variable(torch.zeros(
            self.num_layers, x.size(0), self.hidden_size))       
        c_0 = Variable(torch.zeros(
            self.num_layers, x.size(0), self.hidden_size))      
        # Propagate input through LSTM
        ula, (h_out, _) = self.lstm(x, (h_0, c_0))   
        h_out = h_out.view(-1, self.hidden_size)       
        out = self.fc(h_out)       
        return out

# train lstm model
def trainNet(trainX, trainY, testX, testY, n_epochs, seq_length, learning_rate = 0.01, optimizer_type = 'A'):
    n_epochs = n_epochs
    learning_rate = learning_rate

    # Model Architecture Components
    input_size = 1
    hidden_size = 4
    num_layers = 1

    num_classes = 1

    # Instantiate class GAPforecast object
    model = GAPforecast(num_classes, input_size, hidden_size, num_layers)

    criterion = torch.nn.MSELoss()    # mean-squared error
    if optimizer_type == 'A':
        optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
    else:
        optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)

    # Train the model
    for epoch in range(n_epochs):
        trainloss = 0.0

        outputs = model(trainX)
        optimizer.zero_grad()

        # obtain the loss function
        loss = criterion(outputs, trainY)

        loss.backward()

        optimizer.step()
        trainloss = loss.item()
        if epoch % 100 == 0:
            print("Epoch: %d, \tTraining Loss: %1.5f" % (epoch, loss.item()))

    return model

Conclusion¶

  • It is observed that global active power has decreased year 2010 onwards [shown in fig. global_active_power_actual_yearly.png]
  • The lstm model peformance is best on weekly and monthly aggregated data. The MAPE of the forecast on each of the level on test dataset is as shown in the table.
Time Frame MAPE (%)
Daily 32
Weekly 15
Monthly 15
  • Forecasting global active power at minute level is relatively slow and needs high speed infrastructure to train LSTM.
  • With missing values, the current model performance good enough using LSTM

Scope of Improvement/Future work¶

The current work can be further improved by considering to handle identified challeneges in different ways. The best approach can be identified by designing and conducting experiments. The open items that can further improved are -

  • Fetching actual values of the missing values rather than imputation would ehance model performance.
  • Using pre-trained model on relevant dataset would help to reduce model training time and also, avoid over-fitting of the model.
  • Global active power forcasting at minute and hour level can be done using high speed machine. The infrastructure used in this project were taking longer time training time and thus, can not be explored extensively.
  • Using similar, approach electrical meters readings can be forecasted.
